<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>「应可钧」Kejun Albert Ying</title><link>http://localhost:1314/</link><description>Recent content on 「应可钧」Kejun Albert Ying</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="http://localhost:1314/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>On research taste</title><link>http://localhost:1314/blog/research-taste/</link><pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://localhost:1314/blog/research-taste/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve been thinking about what people mean when they say a scientist has &amp;ldquo;good taste.&amp;rdquo; It comes up a lot in academia, usually as a compliment, but I rarely hear anyone define it clearly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you imagine all the hypotheses and analyses you could pursue right now as a graph, each one a node, with edges representing how one result enables or changes another, then research taste is something like the ability to find the node (or small module) that would affect the largest number of other nodes. It&amp;rsquo;s a search problem over a network.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Contact &amp; About</title><link>http://localhost:1314/about/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://localhost:1314/about/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="contact"&gt;Contact&lt;/h2&gt;
