&lt;h2 id="about"&gt;About&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="avatar.jpg" class="sidenote" style="min-width: initial; margin-top: 0rem;" alt="Kejun Albert Ying"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kejun Ying, postdoctoral researcher studying aging systems biology at &lt;a href="https://med.stanford.edu/"&gt;Stanford University&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href="https://wyss-coray.stanford.edu/"&gt;Wyss-Coray lab&lt;/a&gt;) and &lt;a href="https://www.bakerlab.org/"&gt;Institute for Protein Design&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href="https://www.bakerlab.org/"&gt;Baker lab&lt;/a&gt;), NIH/NIA K00 fellow. Dr. Ying completed his Ph.D. in Biology (2025) and M.S. in Computational Science &amp;amp; Engineering (2024) from &lt;a href="https://hms.harvard.edu/"&gt;Harvard University&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href="https://gladyshevlab.bwh.harvard.edu/"&gt;Dr. Vadim Gladyshev&amp;rsquo;s lab&lt;/a&gt;. His contributions include developing &lt;a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s43587-023-00557-0"&gt;the first causal inference-based aging clock&lt;/a&gt; (Nature Aging cover, 2024), creating &lt;a href="https://clockbase.org"&gt;ClockBase&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a href="https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2023.02.28.530532v1"&gt;preprint&lt;/a&gt;) &amp;ndash; a platform integrating over two million biological age data highlighted in Nature Biotechnology News &amp;ndash; and developing MethylGPT, recognized in Science by Eric Topol as among the most promising biomedical large models. Dr. Ying is a core member of the Biomarkers of Aging Consortium, co-leads its Biolearn and Challenge project. His research has been published in various high-impact journals, including Nature Aging, Nature Review Genetics, Nature Medicine, and Nature Metabolism.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Curriculum Vitae</title><link>http://localhost:1314/cv/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://localhost:1314/cv/</guid><description>&lt;style type="text/css"&gt;
